(1) Learning Rate

Learning Rate is a small value that controls:

How much the ANN should update weights during learning

It decides:

how fast ANN learns
how big the weight changes should be
Simple Meaning

After finding error:

ANN updates weights

Learning rate controls the update size.
=========

Formula

New Weight=Old Weight−Learning Rate×Gradient

Example

Suppose:

Old Weight = 0.8
Gradient = 0.2
Learning Rate = 0.1

Calculation:

New Weight = 0.8 - (0.1 × 0.2)
= 0.8 - 0.02
= 0.78

===========
(2) Gradient Descent

Gradient Descent is an optimization algorithm used to:

Reduce loss/cost function

It helps ANN find best weights.

Simple Meaning

Gradient descent moves weights in the direction where error decreases.

Goal:

Minimum Error
Working Process
1. Predict output
2. Calculate error
3. Find gradient
4. Update weights
5. Repeat
=======


Real-Time Example 

Imagine riding bicycle downhill.

Goal:

Reach lowest valley point

Gradient descent:

checks slope direction
moves downward step by step
finally reaches minimum error point

========

ANN Workflow
Feedforward
     ↓
Loss Function
     ↓
Gradient Descent
     ↓
Update Weights
     ↓
Backpropagation
     ↓
Better Prediction

===============

| Learning Rate             | Gradient Descent     |
| ------------------------- | -------------------- |
| Controls step size        | Optimization method  |
| Decides update speed      | Finds minimum error  |
| Small numeric value       | Complete algorithm   |
| Used during weight update | Used during training |


